00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,296
This demo is a quick walkthrough of valley-k-small, the research

2
00:00:04,296 --> 00:00:08,592
system I use to study first-passage-time distributions in stochastic search,

3
00:00:08,592 --> 00:00:12,888
and why I think this kind of work can become

4
00:00:12,888 --> 00:00:14,176
useful scientific tooling.

5
00:00:14,176 --> 00:00:18,472
The scientific question is simple to state, but rich in

6
00:00:18,472 --> 00:00:22,768
behaviour. If a random walker moves on a ring with

7
00:00:22,768 --> 00:00:27,064
a directed shortcut, how does that geometry reshape the full

8
00:00:27,064 --> 00:00:31,360
distribution of arrival times, not just the mean? I care

9
00:00:31,360 --> 00:00:35,656
about the whole curve: the first peak, the valley between

10
00:00:35,656 --> 00:00:39,952
peaks, the possibility of a second peak, and the parameter

11
00:00:39,952 --> 00:00:42,100
regimes that create those transitions.

12
00:00:42,100 --> 00:00:46,396
What I am proud of here is not only the

13
00:00:46,396 --> 00:00:50,692
mathematics. It is the structure of the project. This is

14
00:00:50,692 --> 00:00:54,988
not a single notebook with a few nice plots. The

15
00:00:54,988 --> 00:00:59,284
repository already separates reports, reusable core code in src slash

16
00:00:59,284 --> 00:01:03,579
vkcore, archives, documentation, and site outputs. Individual report folders then

17
00:01:03,579 --> 00:01:07,875
keep their own code, figures, data, notes, sections, and outputs.

18
00:01:07,875 --> 00:01:11,742
That makes the work reproducible and easier to extend.

19
00:01:11,742 --> 00:01:16,038
The workflow is equally important. I can define a geometry,

20
00:01:16,038 --> 00:01:20,333
sweep a parameter such as beta or shortcut destination, regenerate

21
00:01:20,333 --> 00:01:24,629
outputs, and compare exact and numerical behaviour inside the same

22
00:01:24,629 --> 00:01:28,925
loop. That means I am not relying on visual intuition

23
00:01:28,925 --> 00:01:33,221
alone. I can turn a question into a clean computational

24
00:01:33,221 --> 00:01:36,658
experiment and then into figures and report-ready conclusions.

25
00:01:36,658 --> 00:01:40,954
One example is the beta sweep. By changing only beta,

26
00:01:40,954 --> 00:01:45,250
I can see how peak timings move, how the bimodal

27
00:01:45,250 --> 00:01:49,116
window changes, and how the entire first-passage curve deforms.

28
00:01:49,116 --> 00:01:53,412
Another example is the destination scan, where I vary only

29
00:01:53,412 --> 00:01:57,708
the shortcut destination and compare exact curves, peak locations, and

30
00:01:57,708 --> 00:01:59,426
second-peak behaviour across cases.

31
00:01:59,426 --> 00:02:03,722
The broader point is that I keep the whole distribution

32
00:02:03,722 --> 00:02:08,018
in view. Instead of collapsing everything to one summary statistic,

33
00:02:08,018 --> 00:02:12,314
I can reason about early and late subpopulations, valley depth,

34
00:02:12,314 --> 00:02:16,180
and shortcut-driven transitions in a much more rigorous way.

35
00:02:16,180 --> 00:02:20,476
Why does that matter beyond theory? Because the same pipeline

36
00:02:20,476 --> 00:02:24,772
can become a decision tool. In BioPath, I want to

37
00:02:24,772 --> 00:02:29,068
use movement models and spatial structure to support precision pest

38
00:02:29,068 --> 00:02:33,364
management, especially questions like trap placement and spatial search design.

39
00:02:33,364 --> 00:02:37,660
So this fellowship would not be a pivot away from

40
00:02:37,660 --> 00:02:41,956
my current work. It would be a way to turn

41
00:02:41,956 --> 00:02:46,252
a rigorous research pipeline into a model-based product for real

42
00:02:46,252 --> 00:02:47,970
